## Problem
S3Adapter has several places using `console.error` directly instead of the injected `this.logger.error()`:

```typescript
// Line 317
console.error(`Failed to get metadata for ${path}:`, error);

// Line 406  
console.error(`Failed to create ${path}:`, error);

// Line 457
console.error(`Failed to delete ${path}:`, error);

// Line 479
console.error(`Failed to move ${source} to ${destination}:`, error);

// Line 541
console.error(`Failed to copy ${source} to ${destination}:`, error);
```

This is inconsistent with other methods that correctly use `this.logger.error()`:
- Line 225: `this.logger.error('Failed to list S3 objects', error);`
- Line 240: `this.logger.error('Failed to list S3 buckets', error);`
- Line 641: `this.logger.error(\`Failed to download...\`, error);`
- Line 706: `this.logger.error(\`Failed to upload...\`, error);`

## Impact
- Inconsistent logging behavior
- Cannot be controlled via logger configuration
- Cannot be mocked in tests
- Logs go to console even if logger is configured differently

## Fix
Replace all `console.error` calls with `this.logger.error`:

```typescript
// Before
console.error(`Failed to get metadata for ${path}:`, error);

// After
this.logger.error(`Failed to get metadata for ${path}`, error);
```

